metadata.name: Plantlets #125
metadata.description:
It all started with amazing work of Julien Leonard (https://twitter.com/julleor) and his blogposts explaining some of his explorations. 

All these prompted me to explore the basically a circle packing process combined with pattern replication in my own directions and style. I really liked the results and here I am with a project that is able to produce a wide variety of shapes from ivy plants spreading a cross a wall to city maps.

In this project the color palettes are produced algorithmically so please forgive me when some of them are not that pretty. :)


Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ 1024 x 1024 resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 3 : render @ 3 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- c : show/hide the clipping layer 
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: Reaching #36
metadata.description:
Reach for the stars.

However impossible it may seem, there's always a way. As long as you believe.
Everybody has a way to their stars, and the only way to reach it is to try as hard as you can and believe in yourself. I will forever live by this and believe in it.

A couple of the palettes used in this piece were adapted from the ever great Studio Yorktown, thank you for providing these incredible combinations of colors :)

--

Press spacebar or right click to save an image.

--

Reaching is a piece I dedicate to my recently passed grandmother. Rest in piece, we love you and miss you.

metadata.name: Vents #89
metadata.description:
Near the start of December @Studio Yorktown launched his "Studio Yorktown Color Town Hall" library of wonderful colour palettes.

"You know what this Town Hall needs?" I asked no one in particular, "Vents!". Besides, what's more Christmassy than a good old vent?

Some nice soothing gradients, with a selection of innies and outies, structure, form, and sometimes sharp edges. I humbly suggest aiming to get a set of three 😁

Thank you for everything fxhash in 2022, looking forwards to 2023!

READ MORE: https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/vents

INSTRUCTIONS ::

h - Toggle high-res
n - toggle noise on/off
s - Download and save image

PRINTING INSTRUCTIONS ::

High-res will output a 8,192 x 8,192 image, at 300dpi it should print at...

27.3 x 27.3 inches
69.3 x 69.3 cm

issuer.name: B U B B L E S

metadata.description:
I got the idea for this work from playing Prince of Persia 1989 on the SEGA Genesis console. I was playing when the two-dimensional design and angles caught my attention. The main character moves up and down on walls, platforms, and black holes that are designed with 90-degree angles. The environment was very mysterious and mysterious. There were different paths to take. You have to choose the right path, or you may end up on the wrong path and have to turn back the same way.
So I took paper and a pen and, with my imagination, I designed paths with 90-degree angles. Walls that connect and form different paths. I removed the details to show the depth of the paths, but instead, I tried to add different random modes to them. Using various lines and colors and multicolor, two-color, and monochromatic palettes.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: MECHA BREATH #206
metadata.description:
A special collection for #objkt4objkt 2024

Taking a very simple concept and sticking to it. Here we divide a space in Voronoi cells, extrude the defined polygons in 3D, and then rotate them along one of the polygon's sides.
I was doing research on materials and lighting when I tried this and thought it had some generative merits, and then I heard of the event, so I decided to create a generator with it.
All the colors/tints come from the lights, environment and material properties, the volume themselves are always "white".

Best enjoyed on desktop / Chrome.

!!! Be sure the check the menu that you can find by clicking/tapping the BUTTON in the TOP LEFT !!!
In this menu you'll find some options to customize and experience the artwork, as well as the exports menu.

!!! TO EXPORT CLEAN HIGH RESOLUTION CAPTURES, click the "EXPORTS" button in the menu, select your desired resolution then click the "START CAPTURE" button. This only works when the generator is running in its own window, so be sure to click the "OPEN" button.

2024 - Christophe Ulu Choffel

metadata.name: Temporality #88
metadata.description:
temporality
/ˌtɛmpəˈralɪti/
The state of existing within or having some relationship with time.

Inspired by the patterns and textures formed where land meets water. Swirling river banks, sedimentary plains, estuaries and deltas - sometimes formed in minutes or hours, other times over hundreds of years.

Temporality explores the ideas of impermanence and erosion and the inevitability of change.

As Philip K. Dick writes in A Scanner Darkly:

"Everything in life is just for a while"

Read the accompanying fxtext article for more details on how this collection came about.

= = = = = = = = =

Press [1] to display @ 1400 x 2100 (default)
Press [2] to display @ 4200 x 6300
Press [S] to download the current resolution

metadata.name: Orchard #80
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #146
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Concrete #156
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Penumbra #97
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Lookouts #1
metadata.description:
Lookouts is a generative illustration done 100% in code using p5js. Inspired by my love for travel and minimalist design, this collection is built based on custom shapes filled with solid colors & limited texture.

The accompanying fxtext article (in ‘Mentions’ below) shares more details about the inspiration and development process of this project.

Lookouts renders as a fixed resolution output (2000 x 1666px). Controls (in live view): 
Press [4] to render at 4000 x 3333px
Press [8] to render at 8000 x 6666px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)
